  "opinion": "As a retired man living in New York who has spent most of his life in this city, I’ve seen how conversations about healthcare and vaccines have shifted dramatically over the years. Growing up in a time when health information was often shared through word of mouth and local clinics, I remember my parents never talking about vaccines in the same way people do now. They trusted the doctors they knew, and that trust was built over decades. Today, with the internet and social media, information spreads so fast that it’s easy to get overwhelmed. I find myself spending a few times a month on social media, mostly to check in with family and friends, but I’ve noticed how quickly misinformation can spread, especially around topics like the COVID vaccine. My curiosity drives me to learn more, but my low conscientiousness means I sometimes struggle to stay focused on the facts. I’ve tried to stay calm and open-minded, as my high agreeableness helps me listen to others without judgment. However, my high neuroticism makes me anxious when I hear conflicting opinions, especially from people I care about. I’ve found that talking to my grandchildren about vaccines helps me process the information. They’re young and curious, and their questions make me think more clearly. I try to share what I know without overwhelming them, using simple terms. It’s important to remember that trust is built slowly, just like a well-made painting or a carefully knitted sweater. When I see people getting upset online, I remind myself that we’re all trying to do the right thing, even if we don’t agree. In the end, staying patient and kind, as I do with my knitting and painting, helps me navigate these discussions without letting anxiety take over.",
